Title : Corrina Hewat
Text : '''Corrina Hewat''' (born 21 December 1970, [[Edinburgh]]) is a Scottish harpist and composer<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120428005855/http://harpfestival.co.uk/uncategorized/song-of-the-oak-and-the-ivy-at-celtic-connections "Song of the Oak and the Ivy"]. ''Edmonton International Harp Festival''</ref> who was awarded Music Tutor of the Year at [[Na Trads]] in 2013.<ref>
{{cite web|url=http://projects.scottishcultureonline.com/scotstradmusicawards/voting/|title=MG ALBA Scots Trad Music Awards 2013 -- The Results!|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> She has worked with poet [[Robin Robertson]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Robertson|first=Robin|date=8 Nov 2013|title=Songs of St Kilda|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/nov/08/songs-st-kilda-robin-robertson}}</ref> and has written music for the [[Dunedin Consort]]. She sings with [[Karine Polwart]] and Annie Grace in what they describe as a 'girly trio'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/girlytrio |title=Grace, Hewat & Polwart - UK - A'cappella / Folk / Acoustique - www.myspace.com/girlytrio |publisher=MySpace.com |date= |accessdate=20 Feb 2013}}</ref> and also appeared with Polwart on [[Lau (band)|Lau]]'s 2009 [[Arc Light (album)|Arc Light]] album. She has collaborated with Patsy Reid (original founder of [[Breabach]]) and others as ''The Unusual Suspects''. In July 2008 she performed with [[Bella Hardy]] at London's [[Royal Albert Hall]] as part of the first Folk Prom. In 2006 she appeared on [[Kathryn Tickell]]'s ''The Sky Didnâ€™t Fall'' album.

